A==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading options**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out if I can create an Equinox Framework using a plain JUnit setup. I’m wondering if the system bundle can load my test classes. If I use `configRef.getBundle()`, it returns the system bundle. But when I try to load the CM services, it throws a `ClassNotFound` exception since they aren't in the system bundle. I think I might need to install a synthetic bundle for the CM interfaces or explore boot delegation options for class loading. It feels a bit complicated!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering configuration management setup**\\n\\nI'm thinking that I could simplify things by using the `ExtendedLogServiceManager` to start and register the Configuration Management (CM) with the framework context. The system bundle's `loadClass` might actually find it since it’s launched from the classpath. I know we're not supposed to run tests, but I can reason through the implementation. \\n\\nI need to ensure all lines are covered, especially during constructor initialization and when triggering listener proxies. This includes registering the CM service and retrieving the `SynchronousConfigurationListener`. It's a puzzle, but I'm on the right track!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_yVPeFPIsXvlmOF2KFEnhJ7KN|fc_0c5cf2bd2ea7cb7d0169fa419a5a14819fb3e15e3c2cc74bcf", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge1/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.osgi/3.18.300/main/extracted/org/osgi/service/log/admin/LoggerContext.java", "offset": 1, "limit": 220}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"/home/vjovanov/c/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge1/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.osgi/3.18.300/main/extracted/org/osgi/service/log/admin/LoggerContext.java\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":220}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "mod